{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 20:33:20.299062", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi-tier Clos (fat-tree) EBGP lab\\n\\nSummary / overall health\\n- Data plane (host-level) appears healthy: inter-host ping tests completed with 0% packet loss and low/acceptable RTTs across pods/hosts. No host-level connectivity anomalies observed.\\n- Control plane (BGP) has a clear anomaly localized to one device: spine_router_0_0. BGP on the other routers (the other spine, leaves and the super-spine) is operational and they have full route tables.\\n\\nExecutive finding\\n- spine_router_0_0 is not forming BGP sessions with its expected neighbors (all neighbors shown in Idle state and the BGP table is empty on that router). This is a control-plane/configuration problem on spine_router_0_0, not a general network link failure (interfaces and IPs are up).\\n\\nRelevant observations and evidence\\n\\n1) Host reachability (data-plane)\\n- Aggregate ping results between hosts (pc_0_0 ... pc_3_7) show successful reachability with 0% loss for sampled paths (various 10.x.y.z addresses). No packet loss — indicates forwarding/data-plane connectivity across the topology is functioning.\\n\\n2) spine_router_0_0 BGP state (anomaly)\\n- show ip bgp summary (spine_router_0_0):\\n  - \"BGP router identifier 172.16.0.1, local AS number 65700\"\\n  - Neighbors listed but all in State \"Idle\" and PfxRcd = 0\\n  - Example neighbor line: 172.16.0.0 ... Up/Down \"never\" State/PfxRcd \"Idle\" (same for other neighbors)\\n- Running BGP configuration for spine_router_0_0:\\n  - \"router bgp 65700\" (local AS = 65700)\\n  - configured neighbors (remote-as) include the expected neighbor ASes (65000 for super-spines and various 652xx for leaves).\\n- Host network configuration (spine_router_0_0):\\n  - Interfaces are up and have the expected 172.16.x.x /31 addresses assigned. Kernel routes for the /31 links are present. This supports that the data-plane TCP/IP connectivity of the links is up.\\n\\n3) Other routers show normal BGP behavior\\n- spine_router_0_1 (the other spine) shows a populated BGP table and routes learned:\\n  - local AS = 65101 (from its BGP table output)\\n  - BGP routes present (10.0.0.0/24, etc.), indicating its BGP sessions are established and functioning.\\n- super_spine_router_0 and leaf routers show normal BGP tables and routes learned/advertised.\\n\\nLocalization (faulty device)\\n- Fault localized to: spine_router_0_0 (control-plane / BGP).\\n  - Symptom: none of its EBGP neighbors reach the Established state; BGP table is empty.\\n  - Data-plane on the router (interfaces, addresses) is up, so this is not a physical/link-layer failure.\\n\\nRoot cause (most likely)\\n- Configuration error: spine_router_0_0 has an incorrect BGP local AS configured.\\n  - Evidence: spine_router_0_0 is configured as \"router bgp 65700\" and \"BGP router identifier 172.16.0.1, local AS number 65700\".\\n  - Comparative evidence: the other spine (spine_router_0_1) is using local AS 65101 and is successfully peering with the rest of the topology; super-spine(s) are using AS 65000, leaves use ASes in the 652xx range. The anomalous AS value (65700) on spine_router_0_0 is inconsistent with the expected AS assignments in this lab and corresponds with its failure to establish EBGP sessions with neighbors that are configured to peer with a different spine AS.\\n- Because the neighbor IPs and link addresses are present and kernel routes exist, the failure is not due to missing interfaces or down links. The mismatch in AS configuration (or other BGP misconfiguration) is the primary root cause preventing BGP establishment.\\n\\nImpact / scope\\n- spine_router_0_0 is not advertising/receiving BGP routes (BGP table is empty). Any prefixes that would be learned or forwarded via this spine are being handled by other spines (as seen by other spines and super-spine route tables). Therefore:\\n  - Redundancy/load distribution that would involve spine_router_0_0 is degraded.\\n  - No host connectivity failures were observed at the moment because other spines are handling routes; however the topology is not fully redundant while this spine is out of the BGP control-plane.\\n  - Control-plane inconsistency could affect traffic distribution under failure/traffic-shift scenarios.\\n\\nAdditional notes / logs & data references\\n- Key outputs reviewed:\\n  - Host reachability summary: all sampled host-to-host pings succeeded with 0% loss.\\n  - spine_router_0_0: show ip bgp summary — local AS 65700, all neighbors Idle, PfxRcd 0.\\n  - spine_router_0_0 running-config — \"router bgp 65700\" plus neighbor statements.\\n  - spine_router_0_0 ifconfig/ip addr/ip route — all physical /31 links present and up.\\n  - spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0, leaf routers — normal BGP tables and learned routes (confirming other BGP peers are healthy).\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Network data-plane is healthy and traffic is flowing between hosts.\\n- The anomaly is a BGP control-plane failure on spine_router_0_0: BGP sessions are Idle and no routes are present on that device.\\n- Root cause is most consistent with a configuration error on spine_router_0_0 (incorrect BGP local AS, set to 65700) causing neighbor sessions to fail to establish, despite interfaces being up.\\n\\nIf you want, I can collect any additional targeted outputs/logs (BGP logs, neighbor configs on specific peers, tcpdump of BGP TCP handshake on the /31 link) to further validate the exact reason the BGP FSM is stuck in Idle, but I will not propose or perform remediation unless you ask for mitigation steps., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='fc5700d6-a92a-4c34-bb8b-4a5728666746'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
